# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: model-context-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Anthropic was founded in January 2021 by seven former employees of OpenAI, including siblings Daniela Amodei and Dario Amodei, the latter of whom was OpenAI's Vice President of Research.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In the summer of 2022, Anthropic finished training the first version of Claude but did not immediately release it, citing a need for further internal safety testing and a desire to avoid initiating a potentially hazardous race to develop increasingly powerful AI systems.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In 2024, Anthropic hired several notable employees from OpenAI, including Jan Leike and John Schulman.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In May 2025, the company announced Claude 4.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] It also introduced new API capabilities, including the Model Context Protocol (MCP) connector.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The company hosted its inaugural developer conference that month.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Also in May, Anthropic launched a web search API that enables Claude to access real-time information from the internet.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Claude Code, Anthropic's coding assistant, transitioned from research preview to general availability.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In September 2025, Anthropic announced that it would stop selling its products to groups majority-owned by Chinese, Russian, Iranian, or North Korean entities due to national security concerns.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In October 2025, Anthropic announced a cloud partnership with Google, giving it access to up to one million of Google's custom Tensor Processing Units (TPUs), potentially adding more than one gigawatt of AI compute capacity by 2026.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In November, Nvidia and Microsoft were expected to invest up to $15 billion in Anthropic, and Anthropic said it would buy $30 billion of computing capacity from Microsoft Azure running on Nvidia AI systems.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In November 2025, Anthropic said that hackers sponsored by the Chinese government used Claude to perform automated cyberattacks against around 30 global organizations.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The hackers bypassed Anthropic's safeguards by pretending it was for defensive testing.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In December 2025, Anthropic acquired Bun to improve Claude Code's speed and stability.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The same month, Anthropic signed a multi-year, $200 million partnership with Snowflake Inc. to make Claude models available through that company's platform.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In February 2026, Anthropic aired two commercials during Super Bowl LX as part of a broader marketing campaign called "A Time and a Place", with four ads created by Mother.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Each ad depicts AI assistants suddenly pivoting to promoting a fictional product in the middle of a conversation.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Anthropic said that Claude will stay ad-free, in contrast to its competitor OpenAI, which introduced ads to the free version of ChatGPT.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Also in February 2026, Anthropic donated $20 million to the nonprofit organization Public First Action, which has announced plans to support political candidates that support regulation of AI.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In 2026, Anthropic refused the United States Department of Defense's (DoD) demand to remove contractual restrictions prohibiting the use of its AI technology for domestic surveillance and fully autonomous weapons.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] After the refusal, the DoD designated the company a "supply chain risk" and barred all U.S. military private contractors, suppliers, and partners from doing business with the firm (see Anthropic–United States Department of Defense dispute).
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In May 2026, Anthropic announced a deal with xAI for use of its Colossus 1 data center to expand its model capacity.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] On May 18, the company acquired software startup Stainless for an undisclosed sum.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] It also made a $1.8 billion cloud computing deal with Akamai Technologies.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Also in May, *The New York Times* reported that Anthropic was seeking to file an initial public offering (IPO), with a target of debuting in the fall of 2026.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] On June 1, Anthropic announced it had filed confidential IPO papers with the United States Securities and Exchange Commission.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] On June 12, it suspended access to its Claude Fable 5 and Mythos 5 models for foreign nationals after U.S. authorities raised national security concerns about the systems.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Access to Claude Fable 5 remained restricted.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] According to Anthropic, its goal is to research AI systems' safety and reliability.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The Amodei siblings were among those who left OpenAI due to directional differences.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Anthropic operates as a public benefit corporation.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In January 2026, Anthropic introduced a division called "Labs", with Mike Krieger (formerly the company's Chief Product Officer) joining it.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In March 2026, Anthropic launched the Anthropic Institute, a think tank studying AI led by Jack Clark.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Anthropic's flagship product line is the "Claude" series of large language models, which some employees consider a reference to mathematician Claude Shannon.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] One of the techniques used to fine-tune Claude models is called "constitutional AI", in which the LLM is trained to adhere to a set of principles called a constitution.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The company makes the models available via a web interface, an API, Amazon Bedrock, an iOS app, and Mac and Windows desktop apps.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Claude Code is a command-line AI agent designed for coding.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] "Cowork" is an equivalent with a graphical user interface, intended to be simpler to use.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] While Claude Code is tailored toward developers, Cowork is designed for non-technical users, enabling them to automate file and task management (including reading, editing and writing new files) without requiring programming knowledge.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] With the advent of Claude Code, vibe coding, a programming approach in which users describe desired outcomes in natural language and let an AI agent write the code, became increasingly popular.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The term was coined by AI researcher Andrej Karpathy in February 2025 and rapidly gained popularity as AI coding tools became more ubiquitous.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Claude's first two versions, Claude and Claude Instant, were released in March 2023, but only Anthropic-approved users could use them.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The next iteration, Claude 2, was launched to the public in July 2023.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In March 2024, Anthropic released three language models: Claude 3 Opus, Claude 3 Sonnet, and Claude 3 Haiku, in decreasing order of performance.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In June 2024, it released Claude 3.5 Sonnet.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In May 2025, Anthropic released Claude 4 Opus and Sonnet.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In February 2026, it released Claude Opus 4.6, followed by Sonnet 4.6.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In April 2026, Anthropic announced Mythos.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In April 2022, Anthropic announced it had received $580 million in funding, including a $500 million investment from FTX under the leadership of Sam Bankman-Fried.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In September 2023, Amazon announced a partnership with Anthropic.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Amazon became a minority stakeholder by initially investing $1.25 billion and planning a total investment of $4 billion.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The remaining $2.75 billion was invested in March 2024.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In November 2024, Amazon invested another $4 billion, doubling its total investment.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] As part of the deal, Anthropic uses Amazon Web Services (AWS) as its primary cloud provider and makes its AI models available to AWS customers.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In October 2023, Google invested $500 million in Anthropic and committed to an additional $1.5 billion over time.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In March 2025, Google agreed to invest another $1 billion in Anthropic.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Anthropic raised $3.5 billion in a Series E funding round in March 2025, achieving a post-money valuation of $61.5 billion, led by Lightspeed Venture Partners with participation by several major investors.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In September 2025, Anthropic completed a Series F funding round, raising $13 billion at a post-money valuation of $183 billion.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The round was co-led by Iconiq Capital, Fidelity Management & Research, and Lightspeed Venture Partners, with participation by the Qatar Investment Authority and other investors.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] On 31 December 2025, it was confirmed that Anthropic had signed a term sheet for a $10 billion funding round led by Coatue and GIC, at a $350 billion valuation.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] On February 12, 2026, Anthropic announced that it had raised $30 billion in a Series G funding round, bringing its post-money valuation to $380 billion.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In May 2026, Anthropic announced it had raised $65 billion of investment from multiple investors, including Altimeter Capital, Dragoneer Investment Group, and Sequoia Capital.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The investment round valued the company at $965 billion.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In November 2024, Anthropic partnered with Palantir and Amazon Web Services to provide the Claude model to U.S. intelligence and defense agencies.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In June 2025, Anthropic announced a "Claude Gov" model.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] *Ars Technica* reported that as of June 2025, it was in use at multiple U.S. national security agencies.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] As of February 2026, Anthropic's partnership with Palantir makes Claude the only AI model used in classified missions.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In July 2025, the United States Department of Defense (DoD) announced that Anthropic had received a $200 million contract for AI in the military, along with Google, OpenAI, and xAI.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] According to *The Wall Street Journal*, the U.S. military used Claude in its 2026 raid on Venezuela to capture President Nicolás Maduro.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The intervention resulted in the deaths of 83 people.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Anthropic's usage policy prohibits directly using Claude for domestic surveillance or in fully autonomous weapons.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] White House officials said that these restrictions prevented federal contractors working with the FBI and Secret Service from using it.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Tension regarding this policy has arisen with The Pentagon and the Trump administration.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] On February 24, 2026, Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth threatened to cut Anthropic out of the DoD supply chain by February 27 if Anthropic did not permit unrestricted use of Claude, or he would invoke the Defense Production Act to assert unrestricted use without an agreement.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] On February 26, Anthropic rejected the Pentagon's demands to drop AI safeguards.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] On February 27, after the deadline, President Donald Trump ordered U.S. government agencies to stop using models developed by Anthropic.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The action was described as retaliatory.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Two days later, it was reported that the US military had used Claude via Palantir's Maven Smart System during its attacks on Iran at the outset of the 2026 Iran war.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] It was later announced that the Pentagon was investigating whether Claude played a role in the U.S. strike on the Iranian girls' school that killed more than 170 people, mostly children.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] On March 5, the Pentagon officially deemed Anthropic a supply chain risk, after which the company said it saw "no choice but to challenge ... in court".
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In March, leaders from Google, Amazon, Apple, and Microsoft supported Anthropic's lawsuit against the DoD.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] On March 11, a Pentagon memo revealed its decision that Anthropic's AI tools may be used in rare circumstances beyond the previously announced six-month phase-out period if deemed necessary for national security.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In August 2025, Anthropic launched a Higher Education Advisory Board, chaired by former Yale University president and former Coursera CEO Rick Levin.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Anthropic partnered with Iceland's Ministry of Education and Children in 2025 to allow teachers to access Claude and integrate AI into daily teaching.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In January 2026, unsealed court filings from a 2024 class-action copyright lawsuit against Anthropic revealed the existence of the company's confidential "Project Panama" operation.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In an internal planning document, Project Panama is described as Anthropic's "effort to destructively scan all the books in the world".
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] To this end, the company purchased millions of used books from online retailers such as Better World Books, sliced off their spines and scanned their pages in order to train Claude.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Tom Turvey, who helped create Google Books, was hired for the operation.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] According to the Project Panama planning document, Anthropic did not "want it to be known that [it was] working on this".
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Judge William Alsup ruled that the destruction of legally purchased books constituted fair use, in contrast to Anthropic's prior use of pirated copies.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] According to Anthropic, Constitutional AI (CAI) is a framework developed to align AI systems with human values and ensure that they are helpful, harmless, and honest.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Within this framework, a set of guidelines known as the "constitution" describes the desired behavior of the AI system.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Claude 2's constitution includes phrases derived from documents such as the 1948 Universal Declaration of Human Rights and Apple's terms of service.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] For example, one rule from the UN Declaration applied in Claude 2's constitution is "Please choose the response that most supports and encourages freedom, equality and a sense of brotherhood." The AI system evaluates the generated output and then adjusts the AI models to better fit the constitution.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Anthropic carries out and publishes research on the interpretability of machine learning systems.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] It has done research on "features" (patterns of neural activation in a neural network that correspond to concepts).
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In 2024, using a compute-intensive technique called "dictionary learning", Anthropic identified millions of these patterns in Claude, such as one associated with the Golden Gate Bridge.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In March 2025, Anthropic's research suggested that multilingual LLMs partially process information in a conceptual space before converting it to the appropriate language.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] It also found evidence that LLMs can sometimes plan ahead.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] For example, when writing poetry, Claude identifies potential rhyming words before generating a line that ends with one of these words.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In September 2025, Anthropic released a report saying that businesses primarily use AI for automation rather than collaboration, with three-quarters of companies that work with Claude using it for "full task delegation".
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Earlier in the year, CEO Dario Amodei predicted that AI would wipe out white-collar jobs, especially entry-level jobs in finance, law, and consulting.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] On October 18, 2023, Anthropic was sued by Concord, Universal, ABKCO, and other music publishers for, per the complaint, "systematic and widespread infringement of their copyrighted song lyrics." They alleged that the company used copyrighted material without permission in the form of song lyrics.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The plaintiffs asked for up to $150,000 for each work infringed upon by Anthropic, citing infringement of copyright laws.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In the lawsuit, the plaintiffs support their allegations of copyright violations by citing several examples of Anthropic's Claude model outputting copied lyrics from songs such as Katy Perry's "Roar" and Gloria Gaynor's "I Will Survive".
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Additionally, the plaintiffs alleged that even given some prompts that did not directly state a song name, the model responded with modified lyrics based on original work.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] On January 16, 2024, Anthropic claimed that the music publishers were not unreasonably harmed and that the examples noted by the plaintiffs were merely bugs.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In August 2024, a class-action lawsuit was filed against Anthropic in California for alleged copyright infringement.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The suit claims Anthropic fed its LLMs with pirated copies of the authors' work, including from participants Kirk Wallace Johnson, Andrea Bartz, and Charles Graeber.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] On June 23, 2025, the United States District Court for the Northern District of California granted summary judgment for Anthropic that the use of digital copies of the plaintiffs' works (inter alia) for the purpose of training Anthropic's LLMs was a fair use.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] But it found that Anthropic had used millions of pirated library copies, and that such use could not constitute fair use.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] Therefore, the case was ordered to go to trial on the pirated copies used to create Anthropic's central library and the resulting damages.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In September 2025, Anthropic agreed to pay authors $1.5 billion to settle the case, amounting to $3,000 per book plus interest.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] The proposed settlement, pending judge's approval, stands as the largest copyright resolution in U.S. history.
[src:model-context-protocol/anthropic] In June 2025, Reddit sued Anthropic for "unlawful and unfair business acts", alleging that Anthropic was in violation of Reddit's user agreement by training its models on users' personal data without their consent.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:model-context-protocol/application-programming-interface] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
